# Commit After Every Edit

**Precedence:** standing user instruction. Do not ask; do not batch.

## Default

One edit = one commit. After finishing edits to a file, `git add <path>` + `git commit` **before** editing any other file or running tests.

## Exception 1: project.yml + XcodeGen (one commit)

When you change `project.yml` and run XcodeGen (`xcodegen generate` / `-c`): one commit containing **`project.yml` plus all generated artifacts** from that run (typically `SixLayerFramework.xcodeproj/project.pbxproj`, affected `*.xcscheme`, any other XcodeGen outputs). Treat source + regeneration as one logical edit.

Do **not** split `project.yml` and its generated output across separate commits. Do **not** hand-edit `project.pbxproj` or scheme XML — use the `project.yml` flow. See [project-yml-exclusive.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/project-yml-exclusive.mdc).

## Exception 2: XcodeGen regen only (one commit)

When **`project.yml` is unchanged** but generated Xcode project files drifted: run `xcodegen generate -c`, then one commit with all regenerated artifacts (typically `project.pbxproj`). Do **not** `git restore` or leave the drift uncommitted — regen and commit per [project-yml-exclusive.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/project-yml-exclusive.mdc).

## Exception 3: Xcode-aligned shared schemes (one commit)

When the **only** changes are shared `*.xcscheme` files **Xcode** updated (on open/save — not agent edits): one commit with all touched `*.xcscheme` paths. Message: "Align shared Xcode schemes after Xcode save" or similar. Don't hand-edit scheme XML to match. If `project.pbxproj` also drifted, use Exception 2 — regen from XcodeGen first.

## Rationale

Commits are cheap; lost history and cross-machine re-work are expensive. The exceptions keep `project.yml` and its generated form in lockstep, and batch Xcode's own scheme serialization without hand-edits.
